data.name: label2.Text
data.value:
Forge is a tile-based world building tool that allows you to build diverse levels at the click of a button.
Levels can be built using tiles, which are square sprites that can be placed onto the canvas using the mouse. Each tile must have an individual file containing a JSON data structure relating to its properties. The ‘name’ property defines the display name of the tile. The ‘sprite’ property defines the bitmap image that is associated with a tile and the ‘type’ property defines in which tab the tile will be displayed in within the application. The ‘collidable’ property does nothing.
To add a new tile to the application, I recommend copy-pasting one of the pre-existing tile data files and then modifying that file to your liking. You can refresh the tile toolbox by simply pressing the black ‘reload’ button located on the bottom right hand corner of the window.
After loading tile data, valid tiles will appear in your toolbox, sorted by the ‘type’ property that you had previously defined. Tiles with the same type will be grouped together, allowing you to easily sort and access related tiles. If the application encountered an error while reading the JSON data that you have input, an error message will appear and the tile will not be available for use in the toolbox.
You can select a tile by simply pressed on it with the mouse. Pressing on the editor grid will then draw the selected tile, repositioned and rescaled to fit the closest grid cell. If you make a mistake while building a level, you can simply right-click a grid cell, the tile contained within that grid cell will then be removed.
The toolbar located above the editor contains buttons that can commit some other helpful operations.
The purpose of the paintbrush button is to change the background colour of the editor. Once this button is pressed, a colour dialog box will pop up, prompting you to select a colour. If you want to fine-tune your colour selection, you can expand the colour dialog window, revealing a colour wheel that you can press. Once you have selected a colour, press the ‘OK’ button, the colour dialog window will close and colours of various elements will be modified accordingly.
The pink eraser button will remove all tiles that you have placed on the grid. This is useful when you want to start from scratch without having to right-click all the tiles that you have already placed. You will be asked for confirmation before the tile removal operation is executed.
If you are not satisfied with the number of tiles that you can manipulate, you can very easily change the size of each individual grid cell by pressing the ‘Cell Size’ button. This will allow more or less cells to fit in the editor. The scale that sprites are drawn at will adjust accordingly to ensure that they fit in one grid cell. The choices of grid cell sizes are locked to 32, 16 or 8.
The ‘Content Directory’ button will open the directory on your computer wherein tile data and sprites are stored. This prevents you from having to navigate to this directory manually.
